meta {
  name: GET /ready — dependency readiness
  type: http
  seq: 2
}

get {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/ready
  body: none
  auth: none
}

assert {
  res.status: eq 200
  res.body.ready: eq true
}

docs {
  # Readiness (real dependency checks)

  **What it proves:** the sidecar's dependencies are healthy right now — not
  just that the process booted. Configured dependencies are checked in
  parallel with a 5s timeout per check. Most are probed live per poll; the
  `reranker` instead reports the outcome of the last real rerank made by
  traffic (H.2) — a per-poll Cohere call would burn rate-limited quota and
  cost money without proving anything traffic wouldn't:

  | Dependency  | Probe                                                        |
  |-------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
  | `openemr`   | FHIR capability statement (`/apis/default/fhir/metadata`)     |
  | `anthropic` | Model list — cheapest authenticated call, proves the key is live |
  | `langfuse`  | `/api/public/health` on the configured Langfuse host          |
  | `postgres`  | `SELECT 1` through the live connection pool                   |
  | `redis`     | Placeholder — reports `not_configured` until a queue is adopted |
  | `document_storage` | OpenEMR password-grant token mint (cached provider) |
  | `retriever_index`  | Fails when the guideline index holds zero chunks |
  | `reranker`  | Last observed real rerank outcome; `ok` + detail `keyed (unverified since boot — no rerank traffic yet)` until first use, `failed` after a failure more recent than the last success |

  **Expected response** — `200`:

  ```json
  {
    "ready": true,
    "dependencies": {
      "openemr":   { "status": "ok" },
      "anthropic": { "status": "ok" },
      "langfuse":  { "status": "ok" },
      "postgres":  { "status": "ok" },
      "redis":     { "status": "not_configured" }
    }
  }
  ```

  **Per-dependency statuses:** `ok` (probe passed — may carry a `detail`
  string, e.g. the reranker's `keyed (unverified since boot …)`), `failed`
  (configured but the check errored — an `error` string says why), or
  `not_configured` (no credentials/URL set for it).

  **When it 503s:** any configured dependency reporting `failed` flips
  `ready` to `false`, as does running in production with a required
  dependency (`openemr`, `anthropic`) unconfigured. On a 503, the
  `dependencies` map pinpoints exactly which check failed and with what
  error — no log archaeology needed.
}
